### Tested versions

Reproducible in v4.4.stable.mono.official [4c311cbee]

### System information

Godot v4.4.stable.mono - Windows 10 (build 19045) - Multi-window, 3 monitors - Vulkan (Forward+) - dedicated NVIDIA GeForce RTX 3070 Ti (NVIDIA; 32.0.15.7283) - Intel(R) Core(TM) i9-10900K CPU @ 3.70GHz (20 threads)

### Issue description

Overriding `_GetRid()` on a class directly extending `Material` does not affect the result of `GetRid()`. In my test, `GetRid()` always returns `0`.

This is either a documentation error, or a bug in the behavior. The documentation for `_GetRid()` states:
> Override this method to return a custom `Rid` when `GetRid()` is called.

This does not reflect upon what is observed.

### Steps to reproduce

1. Create a new C# script. Set its contents to this:

```cs
using Godot;
[Tool, GlobalClass]
public sealed partial class TestMaterial : Material {

	private Rid _myCustomRid;
	private Rid _shaderRidToAppeaseOverload;

	public TestMaterial() {
		_myCustomRid = RenderingServer.MaterialCreate();
		_shaderRidToAppeaseOverload = RenderingServer.ShaderCreate();
		// ^ I just need a valid Rid

		if (GetRid() != _GetRid()) {
			GD.PrintErr("Well this is awkward.");
		}
	}

	public override Shader.Mode _GetShaderMode() => Shader.Mode.Spatial;
	public override Rid _GetShaderRid() => _shaderRidToAppeaseOverload;
	public override Rid _GetRid() => _myCustomRid;


}
```

2. Build the project and restart the editor.
3. Create a new Resource of type `TestMaterial` as you would any other resource, by right clicking in the file panel.
4. Observe the output log. A message reading "Well this is awkward." will display, indicating the results of the two methods are different.

